
[1]snare

   SNARE, n.

   1. An instrument for catching animals, particularly fowls, by the leg.
   It consists of a cord or string with slip-knots, in which the leg is
   entangled. A snare is not a net.

   2. Any thing by which one is entangled and brought into troble. I Cor.
   7. A fool's lip are the snare of his soul. Prov. 18.

    SNARE, v.t. To catch with a snare; to ensnare; to entangle; to bring
   into unexpected evil, perplexity or danger. The wicked is snared in the
                        work of his own hands. Ps. 9.
